<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-400-022  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 400 022.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  May 3 1990 v139 pA1(N) pA1(L) 25 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. seeks to ease technology sales in Eastern Europe; computersfor Soviets; business interests urge even freer commerce - some inPentagon opposed.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Farnsworth, Clyde H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Bush administration has proposed to relax export controls onadvanced technological products to Eastern Europe and the SovietUnion.andP;  Business leaders in the computer and communicationsindustries have expressed concern that current export controls arelimiting overseas markets for products such as computers andcommunications equipment.andP;  Members of the House Foreign AffairsCommittee, who are expected to draft legislation that willliberalize export controls, have expressed that theadministration's proposals do not go far enough.andP;  Some Pentagonofficials are concerned that the technology transfer may havemilitary applications for the Soviet Union.andP;  The CoordinatingCommittee on Multilateral Export Controls (Cocom) will review theadministration's proposal in Jun 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Europe, EasternSoviet UnionTechnology transferCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsComputersUnited States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign AffairsComputer IndustryPolitical IssuesGovernment RegulationCommunications IndustryUnited States. Department of DefenseUnited States.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>